<section id="problem-statement" class="content-section">
  <div class="section-container">
    <h2 class="section-heading reveal">Abstract</h2>

    <div class="prose reveal">
      <!-- TODO: Replace with your actual problem statement paragraph 1 -->
      <p>
         Mobile robots increasingly operate in open-world
environments where rare failures and near-misses are in-
evitable. To ensure that each failure becomes a once-in-a-
lifetime event, the central bottleneck is faithfully reconstructing
what the robot perceived, estimated, and decided at critical
moments. Existing recorders either miss internal autonomy
evidence or cannot sustain always-on capture within onboard
budgets, and vibration can corrupt sensor data and make replay
“fail differently” than online behavior. We present VibraBox, a
vibration-aware robot Black Box for deployable, perception-
faithful replay. VibraBox provides an event-driven two-mode
recorder: always-on bounded buffering in “routine mode” and
trigger-to-commit pre/during/post-event persistence in “Black
Box mode” to retain critical pre-event cues for diagnosis; it
then makes each event package replay-sufficient yet storage-
efficient via a three-stage data-plane optimization that removes
temporal/spatial redundancy at the frame/point/byte levels, and
a vibration-aware control plane that adapts logging to mobility-
induced vibration. On a robotic vehicle across indoor/outdoor
routes spanning low to high vibration, VibraBox makes always-
on persistence practical (up to 46% storage reduction, 52%
lower CPU, and 51.7% lower end-to-end latency) while im-
proving replay stability (up to 50% lower trajectory error
and 71.4% lower rotational drift). It further improves seman-
tic preservation (online-vs-replay consistency) and robustness
across mainstream LiDAR detectors, and outperforms repre-
sentative baselines end-to-end. 
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="abstract" class="content-section">
  <div class="section-container">
    <h2 class="section-heading reveal">Research Questions</h2>

    <div class="prose reveal">
      <p>
        We propose <strong>VibraBox</strong>, a vibration-aware robot Black Box that enables efficient yet perception-faithful 
        recording under real-world disturbances. It is guided by three system-level research questions:
      </p>

      <p>
        (<strong>i</strong>) <strong>RQ<sub>1</sub>:</strong> 
        How to <em>record</em> continuously within bounded resources while preserving pre/during/post-event context;
      </p>

      <p>
        (<strong>ii</strong>) <strong>RQ<sub>2</sub>:</strong> 
        How to <em>remove</em> temporal and spatial redundancy without sacrificing downstream replay fidelity for 
        downstream perception and localization; this directly targets failure modes that cause robustness to collapse in real deployments.
      </p>

      <p>
        (<strong>iii</strong>) <strong>RQ<sub>3</sub>:</strong> 
        How to <em>adapt</em> to vibration-induced corruption so replay remains consistent with online behavior.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>






